<!-- SECTION 2: OVERVIEW / INTRO + TL;DR -->
<section class="content-section" id="overview-section">
    <div class="content-container">
        <div class="text-content">
            <h2 class="section-title">Pvt Ltd to Public Ltd Conversion in Delhi - Overview</h2>
            <div class="content-text">
                <div class="highlight-box" style="margin-bottom:20px;">
                    <p><strong>&#128204; TL;DR - Pvt to Public Ltd Conversion Services at a Glance</strong></p>
                    <p>A Private Limited Company is converted to a Public Limited Company under Section 14 read with Section 18 of the Companies Act 2013 and Rule 33 of the Companies (Incorporation) Rules 2014. The procedure requires special resolution at EGM, filing of Form MGT-14 within 30 days and Form INC-27 within 15 days. No Regional Director approval required. Timeline 4 to 8 weeks. Patron INR 49,999 fixed.</p>
                </div>
                <p><div class='table-responsive-wrapper'>
                <table>
                    <thead><tr><th>Quick Reference</th><th>Details</th></tr></thead>
                    <tbody>
                        <tr><td>Governing Laws</td><td>Companies Act 2013 - Section 13 (MOA alteration), Section 14 (AOA alteration - charging), Section 18 (conversion preserves body corporate), Section 117 (resolution filing), Section 2(71) (Public Company), Section 3 (7 members), Section 149 (3 directors) + Rule 33 Companies (Incorporation) Rules 2014</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Applicable To</td><td>Any Delhi Pvt Ltd meeting post-conversion eligibility - minimum 7 shareholders, minimum 3 directors (1 Indian resident); planning IPO, public capital raise, strategic M&A or institutional fundraising</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Timeline</td><td>End-to-end 4 to 8 weeks. 21 clear days EGM notice is the largest fixed component</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Cost (Patron)</td><td>INR 49,999 FIXED (Exl GST and Govt. Charges) - end-to-end Section 14 conversion</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Authority</td><td>ROC NCT of Delhi and Haryana, CGO Complex - NO Regional Director involvement</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Special Resolution Threshold</td><td>75% (three-fourths) majority at EGM (Section 114(2))</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Core Forms</td><td>MGT-14 within 30 days (Section 117); INC-27 within 15 days (Rule 33)</td></tr>
                    </tbody>
                </table>
                </div></p>
                <p>A Private Limited Company is the right vehicle for the bootstrap-to-Series-B journey - restricted share transfer, capped at 200 members, no public capital access, but light governance load (no mandatory independent directors below thresholds, no audit committee below thresholds, no SEBI scrutiny). The right reasons to convert to Public Limited are specific - readying for IPO listing, accessing public capital via Follow-on Public Offer (FPO) or rights issue at scale, strategic M&A where the acquirer or target requires Public Limited status, brand and credibility upgrade for institutional buyers (often required for PSU tenders and large corporate procurement) or ESOP rollout to a wider employee base beyond the 200-member cap. The procedure itself is materially simpler than the reverse direction - Public-to-Private requires Regional Director approval, newspaper publication and a 21-day objection window. Pvt-to-Public needs only board resolution, special resolution at EGM, Form MGT-14 within 30 days and Form INC-27 within 15 days of the special resolution under Rule 33.</p>
                <p>Content is reviewed quarterly for accuracy.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

<!-- SECTION 3: WHAT IS GSTAT APPEAL FILING -->
<section class="content-section" id="what-section">
    <div class="content-container">
        <div class="two-column">
            <div class="column-content">
                <h2 class="section-title">How Private Limited Becomes Public Limited Under Section 14</h2>
                <div class="content-text what-is-definition">
                    
                    <p>Conversion of a Private Limited Company to a Public Limited Company is the statutory process under which an existing Private Limited Company alters its Articles of Association under Section 14 of the Companies Act 2013, with corresponding amendments to the Memorandum under Section 13. The legal characterisation under Section 18 is that the company continues as the same body corporate - the Corporate Identification Number changes only in the company-type segment, but the CIN root, all assets, liabilities, contracts, employees, pending tax assessments and other compliance carry forward unbroken. Section 117 mandates filing of the special resolution in Form MGT-14 within 30 days and Rule 33 of the Companies (Incorporation) Rules 2014 mandates filing of Form INC-27 within 15 days of the special resolution.</p>

<p>The critical procedural advantage of this direction (versus Public-to-Private) is that the Section 14 proviso requiring Central Government / Regional Director approval applies ONLY to the conversion of a public company into a private company - it does NOT apply to the upgrade direction. There is no Regional Director hearing, no Form RD-1, no Form INC-28, no newspaper publication of INC-25A, no individual creditor notice in INC-26 and no 21-day objection window. The procedure is simply - board resolution to convene EGM, EGM with 21 clear days of notice, special resolution at the EGM (75 percent majority of members present and voting), MGT-14 filing with ROC within 30 days, INC-27 filing with ROC within 15 days of the special resolution and ROC issuing a fresh Certificate of Incorporation reflecting the new Public Limited name (the suffix changes from "Private Limited" to "Limited").</p>

<p>The catch is at the eligibility end - a Public Limited Company requires minimum 7 shareholders (under Section 3(1)(a)) versus the current 2 for Pvt Ltd and minimum 3 directors (under Section 149(1)(b)) versus 2 for Pvt Ltd, with at least 1 director being an Indian resident under Section 149(3). Most Pvt-to-Public conversions therefore include a pre-conversion share allotment (via Form PAS-3) to expand the shareholder base to 7 and additional director appointments (via Form DIR-12) to reach 3 directors. Delhi anchors this engagement because ROC NCT of Delhi and Haryana at CGO Complex, Lodhi Road handles the filings and the highest concentration of Delhi-NCR growth-stage Private Limited Companies preparing for IPO and large institutional rounds is in this jurisdiction.</p>

                </div>
                <div class="highlight-box" style="margin-top:20px;">
                    <p><strong>Key Terms for Pvt to Public Ltd Conversion:</strong></p>
                    <p><strong>Section 14 Companies Act 2013:</strong> Charging section for alteration of Articles; the proviso requiring Central Government approval applies only to the reverse direction (Public to Private).</p>
<p><strong>Section 18 Companies Act 2013:</strong> Recognises conversion as a change of company type that preserves the body corporate; assets, liabilities, contracts and proceedings carry forward.</p>
<p><strong>Section 2(71) Public Company:</strong> A company which is not a private company; shareholder base unlimited; share transfers free; public invitation for securities permitted (SEBI for listed).</p>
<p><strong>Section 3 - Minimum Members:</strong> 7 for Public Limited (versus 2 for Pvt Ltd); maximum unlimited.</p>
<p><strong>Section 149 - Directors:</strong> Minimum 3 for Public Limited (versus 2 for Pvt Ltd); at least 1 Indian resident under Section 149(3).</p>
<p><strong>Section 149(4) Independent Directors:</strong> Mandatory for listed; for unlisted - above INR 10 crore paid-up capital OR INR 100 crore turnover OR INR 50 crore loans / debentures / deposits.</p>
<p><strong>Section 177 Audit Committee:</strong> Mandatory for listed and unlisted above the same thresholds; chaired by an independent director.</p>
<p><strong>Section 178 NRC:</strong> Nomination and Remuneration Committee - same thresholds; minimum 3 non-executive directors with majority independent.</p>
<p><strong>Rule 33 Companies (Incorporation) Rules 2014:</strong> Form INC-27 filing for Pvt-to-Public conversion within 15 days of the special resolution.</p>
<p><strong>Form MGT-14:</strong> Special resolution filing with ROC within 30 days under Section 117.</p>
<p><strong>Special Resolution:</strong> 75% (three-fourths) majority at EGM with 21 clear days notice (Section 114(2)).</p>

                </div>
            </div>
