<!-- SECTION 4: WHO CAN FILE -->
<section class="content-section" id="who-section">
    <div class="content-container">
        <div class="text-content">
            <h2 class="section-title">Which Private Limited Companies Should Convert (and Which Should Not)</h2>
            <div class="content-text">
                
                <p>Conversion to Public Limited is HIGH-VALUE for the following Delhi-NCR Private Limited Company profiles:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Companies preparing for IPO listing in the next 12-24 months:</strong> Public Limited status is a precondition; SEBI requires at least 1 year as a Public Limited Company before draft red herring prospectus filing in many cases.</li>
                    <li><strong>Companies planning a large equity raise via private placement:</strong> To institutional investors at scale where the Public Limited brand and unlimited shareholder cap helps.</li>
                    <li><strong>Companies in strategic M&A discussions:</strong> Where the acquirer requires Public Limited status (often the case for cross-border acquirers or for tender-led acquisitions in regulated sectors).</li>
                    <li><strong>Companies hitting or approaching the 200-member cap:</strong> Particularly ESOP-heavy growth-stage companies where employee shareholders are about to exceed 200 under Section 2(68).</li>
                    <li><strong>Companies bidding for PSU tenders or large corporate procurement:</strong> Where Public Limited status is mandated or preferred in the qualification criteria.</li>
                    <li><strong>Companies above the INR 100 crore turnover / INR 10 crore paid-up capital scale:</strong> Public Limited governance burden (independent directors, audit committee, NRC) is operationally manageable and the credibility benefit justifies it.</li>
                </ul>
                <p style="margin-top:16px;"><strong>NOT optimal for:</strong> Companies under INR 50 crore turnover with no near-term IPO or institutional plan; companies that cannot identify 5 additional genuine shareholders (to reach 7) without nominee dilution; companies that cannot identify a qualified third director willing to take fiduciary responsibility; companies where founders prefer tight control and restricted share transferability; companies whose IPO timeline is 3+ years out (premature conversion accrues governance costs without proportionate benefits); companies in regulated sectors (NBFC, insurance, banking) where Public Limited conversion triggers sector-specific approvals (RBI, IRDAI) that take 6-12 months independently.</p>

            </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

