<!-- SECTION 9: CHALLENGES -->
<section class="content-section" id="challenges-section">
    <div class="content-container">
        <div class="text-content">
            <h2 class="section-title">Common Challenges and Patron Solutions</h2>
            <div class="content-text">
                <div class="table-responsive-wrapper">
                <table>
                    <thead><tr><th>Challenge</th><th>Impact</th><th>How Patron Accounting Solves It</th></tr></thead>
                    <tbody>
                        <tr><td>Reaching minimum 7 shareholders without diluting founder control</td><td>Many Pvt Ltd Companies operate with 2-4 shareholders (founders, co-founders, ESOP trust); expanding to 7 genuine shareholders requires careful planning to avoid nominee structures that create governance dilution and INC-27 scrutiny issues.</td><td>Patron expands via (a) ESOP trust nominee allocations becoming direct allocations to senior employees, (b) family member allotments via gift or sale, (c) angel or advisory shareholder small allotment or (d) splitting founder holdings between multiple family entities. Each adds a real shareholder without changing economic control; founders' voting majority preserved through MOA / AOA structure and Section 43 share class differentiation.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Reaching minimum 3 directors with a genuinely qualified third director</td><td>Paper appointments expose the third director to personal liability under Section 166 (duties of directors) and Section 447 (fraud penalties); third director needs to take real fiduciary responsibility, not act as a placeholder.</td><td>Patron identifies the third director from the company's genuine governance circle - senior advisor, mentor, family business head or industry expert. Brief them on Section 166 duties, Section 447 risks and post-conversion expectations (4 board meetings per year, AOC-4 signing accountability). DSC and DIN procurement; DIR-12 filing for appointment.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Post-conversion independent director appointment if thresholds crossed</td><td>Section 149(4) plus Rule 4 thresholds (INR 10 crore paid-up capital OR INR 100 crore turnover OR INR 50 crore aggregate outstanding loans / debentures / deposits) are commonly crossed for growth-stage companies; independent directors must be appointed within stipulated timelines post crossing.</td><td>Patron assesses threshold crossing at engagement start - is the company above or below at the date of conversion and what is the projected position in the next 24 months. If thresholds will be crossed within 6 months, independent director candidates identified pre-conversion and appointed alongside the Public Limited conversion itself, avoiding a second governance event.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Pre-conversion Pvt Ltd assessments still open</td><td>If the Pvt Ltd had tax notices, GST notices or pending litigation, these carry forward to the Public Limited under Section 18 - some Public-Limited-specific scrutiny may compound exposure.</td><td>Patron maps pending assessments / litigation / notices at engagement start and discloses the full status in the INC-27 application. Where Pvt Ltd-specific positions (e.g., MAT credit not yet claimed) are at risk in the Public Limited context, they are closed through assessment finalisation or written explanations before conversion. Pending positions do not bar the conversion but are surfaced honestly.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Share transferability change post-conversion</td><td>The Pvt Ltd AOA typically has share transfer restrictions (right of first refusal, board approval, founder pre-emption); the Public Limited AOA must remove these restrictions or limit them carefully to remain consistent with Section 2(71); existing shareholders may resist.</td><td>Patron drafts the Public Limited AOA to retain reasonable pre-emption rights between existing shareholders (legal under Section 58 free transferability with shareholder agreement carve-outs) while removing the absolute restrictions under Section 2(68)(i). Founder lock-in agreements are layered as separate shareholder agreements rather than AOA provisions. Existing shareholders sign updated agreements at the EGM.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>MGT-14 / INC-27 filing deadline slippage</td><td>MGT-14 must be filed within 30 days of the special resolution under Section 117; INC-27 within 15 days under Rule 33. Late filing attracts additional fees and may complicate the ROC review of INC-27.</td><td>Patron's filing calendar locks the EGM date relative to the projected MGT-14 (within 30 days) and INC-27 (within 15 days) deadlines from engagement start. Filings are typically completed within the first 10 days post-EGM rather than at the deadline edge, leaving buffer for ROC queries.</td></tr>

                    </tbody>
                </table>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

