                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-1">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">How do you convert a Private Limited Company to a Public Limited Company in India?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>Pass a special resolution at the EGM with 75 percent majority altering the MOA and AOA (Section 14 read with Section 18 of Companies Act 2013); file Form MGT-14 with ROC within 30 days under Section 117; file Form INC-27 with ROC within 15 days under Rule 33 of Companies (Incorporation) Rules 2014. ROC issues a fresh Certificate of Incorporation reflecting the new Public Limited name. End-to-end 4 to 8 weeks.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-2">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">What is the procedure for Private to Public Limited conversion in 2026?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>Five steps - (a) board resolution to convene EGM, (b) EGM with 21 clear days of notice and special resolution at 75 percent majority altering MOA and AOA, (c) MGT-14 filing with ROC within 30 days, (d) INC-27 filing with ROC within 15 days, (e) ROC issues fresh Certificate of Incorporation. Pre-step - ensure 7 shareholders and 3 directors are in place (with 1 Indian resident).</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-3">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">How many shareholders and directors does a Public Limited Company need?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>Minimum 7 shareholders under Section 3(1)(a) and minimum 3 directors under Section 149(1)(b) of the Companies Act 2013. At least 1 director must be ordinarily resident in India under Section 149(3) - i.e., stayed in India 182 days or more during the previous financial year. There is no upper limit on shareholders or directors.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-4">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">How long does Private to Public Limited conversion take?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>End-to-end timeline is 4 to 8 weeks. Companies with existing 7+ shareholders and 3+ directors complete in 4 to 6 weeks. Companies needing pre-conversion shareholder base expansion (PAS-3 fresh allotment) or new director appointments (DIR-3 plus DIR-12) take 6 to 8 weeks. The 21 clear days of EGM notice is the largest fixed timeline component.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-5">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">Does a Private to Public conversion require Regional Director approval?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>No. The Section 14 proviso requiring Central Government / Regional Director approval applies only to the reverse direction - Public to Private. For Private to Public, only ROC filings are needed - MGT-14 within 30 days and INC-27 within 15 days of the special resolution. This makes the upgrade direction materially simpler and faster than the downgrade direction.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-6">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">What changes after a Pvt Ltd converts to Public Ltd?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>Name suffix changes from 'Private Limited' to 'Limited'. Share transfer restrictions removed; member cap removed (was 200). Above thresholds (INR 10 crore paid-up capital OR INR 100 crore turnover OR INR 50 crore loans / debentures / deposits) - independent directors under Section 149(4), audit committee under Section 177 and Nomination and Remuneration Committee under Section 178 become mandatory. SEBI LODR if eventually listed.</p></div>
